      <div class="faq-grid">
        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Is the Community Edition really free?</h3>
          <p>
            Yes! Our Community Edition is our managed cloud offering that's free
            to use with generous limits. We also offer a fully open source
            version for complete self-hosting control.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What counts as a workspace?</h3>
          <p>
            A workspace is an isolated environment for organizing your MCP
            servers, team members, and projects. Think of it like a separate
            team within NimbleTools.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What counts as a server?</h3>
          <p>
            A server is a running MCP server instance that provides tools and
            resources to AI agents. Each unique MCP server deployment counts as
            one server, regardless of how many agents connect to it.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What counts as an MCP call?</h3>
          <p>
            An MCP call is any request made by an AI agent to your MCP server -
            whether it's calling a tool, accessing a resource, or any other
            interaction. We count both successful and failed requests.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Do you charge per seat?</h3>
          <p>
            No! We're a usage-based pricing platform. You pay based on
            workspaces, servers, and MCP calls - not the number of team members
            or users accessing your account.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Can I deploy in my own cloud?</h3>
          <p>
            Yes! You can self-host using our open source version for complete
            control, or choose Enterprise for managed deployment in your own
            AWS, Azure, or GCP environment with full support and compliance
            features.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
